Part I - Ford GoBike System Exploration¶

by Ammar Yasser¶

Introduction¶

The Ford GoBike System dataset contains bike trip data from the San Francisco Bay Area. It includes information on trip duration, start and end locations, and user type. This data can help explore bike usage patterns in the city.

Loop through the dictionary and convert each column

In [104]:
def convert_data_types(df, conversion_dict):
    for column, dtype in conversion_dict.items():
        if dtype == 'datetime':
            df[column] = pd.to_datetime(df[column], errors='coerce')
        elif dtype == 'category':
            df[column] = df[column].astype('category')
        elif dtype == 'int64':
            df[column] = df[column].astype('int64')
    return df

handling missing values¶

In [109]:
def handle_missing_values(df):
    df.dropna(subset=['start_station_id', 'end_station_id'], inplace=True)
    df['member_birth_year'].fillna(df['member_birth_year'].median(), inplace=True)
    df['member_gender'] = df['member_gender'].cat.add_categories('Unknown')
    df['member_gender'].fillna('Unknown', inplace=True)
    return df

# Usage
df = handle_missing_values(df)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 183,412 records with 16 features including:

  1. duration_sec: the duration of the trip in seconds

  2. start_time: the date and time when the trip started

  3. end_time: the date and time when the trip ended

  4. start_station_id: The unique identifier for the station where the trip began

  5. start_station_name: the name of the station where the trip began

  6. start_station_latitude: The latitude coordinate of the start station

  7. start_station_longitude: The longitude coordinate of the start station

  8. end_station_id: the unique identifier for the station where the trip ended

  9. end_station_name: The name of the station where the trip ended

  10. end_station_latitude: The latitude coordinate of the end station

  11. end_station_longitude: The longitude coordinate of the end station

  12. bike_id: The unique identifier for the bike used during the trip

  13. user_type: The type of user: "Subscriber" for members or "Customer" for casual users

  14. member_birth_year: The birth year of the user

  15. member_gender: The gender of the user

  16. bike_share_for_all_trip: Indicates whether the trip was part of the "Bike Share for All" program which offers discounted memberships to low income residents

Column descriptions were adapted from Zhou (n.d.), who documented the dataset in the GitHub repository Bike System Data Exploration[https://github.com/chefZau/Bike-System-Data-Exploration] ,with additional enhancements to improve clarity and detail.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest are the trip duration, start and end stations, user type, and start time, as they provide key insights into bike usage patterns

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features like end time, member birth year, gender, and bike-sharing status will help support the investigation by providing context on user demographics and trip patterns

In [114]:
# Check for skewness
skewness = df['duration_sec'].skew()

# Plot original distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.histplot(df['duration_sec'], bins=50, kde=True)
plt.xlim(0, 5000)  # limiting to 5000 sec for better visibility
plt.xlabel('Trip Duration (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title(f'Original Distribution of Trip Duration (Skewness: {skewness:.2f})')

# If the skewness is high, apply log transformation
if skewness > 1:
    df['log_duration_sec'] = np.log1p(df['duration_sec'])  # log(1 + x) to handle zero values
    log_skewness = df['log_duration_sec'].skew()

    # Plot log-transformed distribution
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.histplot(df['log_duration_sec'], bins=50, kde=True)
    plt.xlabel('Log(Trip Duration)')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title(f'Log-Transformed Trip Duration (Skewness: {log_skewness:.2f})')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • Due to the high right skew, a log transformation was applied to normalize the distribution, making it closer to a bell-shaped curve.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

the trip duration distribution is highly right-skewed, with most trips lasting under 1000 seconds (~16 minutes) but some extending beyond 5000 seconds (~83 minutes). These long trips could be outliers, possibly due to unusual usage patterns or errors in trip logging. A log transformation could help visualize the data more effectively

The member birth year distribution shows that most users were born between 1980 and 2000, but there are some unrealistic values, such as birth years before 1900, which are likely data entry errors. These values may need to be removed or corrected

For categorical variables, the user type distribution is highly imbalanced, with far more subscribers than customers, indicating that most users are regular riders rather than occasional ones

The bike share for all trips feature shows that most users do not share bikes for all trips, suggesting that bike-sharing is used primarily for individual rides rather than group use

The gender distribution is also skewed, with more male riders than female riders, which might indicate a demographic trend in bike usage

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes some features had unusual distributions that required attention like: Trip Duration: Since the distribution is highly skewed, a log transformation could be applied to normalize the data and make trends more apparent.

Member Birth Year: Some values were implausibly old (before 1900), likely due to data entry errors. These would need to be cleaned or removed to avoid misleading analysis

Categorical Features (User Type, Bike Share Status, Gender): These distributions were mostly expected, but the imbalance in user type (subscribers vs. customers) might require resampling in certain analyses to prevent bias.

3rd Question: What’s the Peak Usage Pattern for Each Day of the Week?¶

In [121]:
# Heatmap of bike usage by day and hour
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
df['weekday'] = df['start_time'].dt.day_name()
df['hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour
usage_pattern = df.pivot_table(index='hour', columns='weekday', aggfunc='size', fill_value=0)

plt.xlabel('Day of the Week')
plt.ylabel('Hour of the Day')
plt.title('Peak Bike Usage by Day and Hour')
plt.show()

  • Weekday peaks appear at morning and evening rush hours (8 AM & 5-6 PM).

  • Weekends have higher afternoon activity (12 PM - 4 PM).

  • Late-night rides are uncommon, with usage dropping significantly after 10 PM.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In this prt of the investigation, several relationships were observed that provided deeeeper insights into bike usage patterns. For instance, the relationship between ride duration and user type revealed that customers (casual riders) generally take longer trips compared to subscribers, who exhibit more consistent trip durations throughout the day. This distinction was further strengthened by analyzing trip durations across different times of the day, where it was evident that ride durations tend to be longer during early morning hours (before 6 AM) and late at night.

additionally, the interaction between gender and trip duration showed that males and females have similar median trip durations, but the "Other" category exhibited higher variation in trip duration. However, the sample size for this group is likely smaller, which may influence these findings. Furthermore, the analysis of trip duration by hour of the day for different user types highlighted that subscribers maintain shorter and more consistent trips, while customers tend to have longer trips, especially in the afternoon and evening.

These Relationships collectively strengthen the understanding of how various factors such as user type, time of day, and demographics influence bike usage patterns.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

yes, there were several interesting and surprising interactions uncovered during the exploration. One notable finding was the difference in peak usage patterns between weekdays and weekends. Weekdays demonstrated clear peaks during morning and evening rush hours (8 AM and 5-6 PM), aligning with commuter behavior. In contrast, weekends showed higher activity levels in the afternoon (12 PM - 4 PM), suggesting that weekend trips are more likely to be recreational rather than work-related.

Another intriguing observation was the disparity in trip duration between subscribers and customers. Subscribers consistently took shorter trips with less variation, indicating regular commuting patterns, while customers exhibited longer and more varied trip durations, possibly due to leisure or recreational purposes.

Moreover, the analysis of bike share for all trips revealed that most users do not share bikes for all trips, implying that bike-sharing is primarily used for individual rides rather than group activities. This finding was unexpected and highlights the predominantly personal nature of bike usage in the dataset.

Conclusions¶

  1. Trip Duration Distribution: The majority of trips lasted under 1000 seconds (~16 minutes), but some extended beyond 5000 seconds (~83 minutes). A log transformation was applied to normalize the distribution and make trends more apparent.

  2. User Type Distribution: Most users were subscribers, meaning they use the service regularly. Customers (occasional riders) represented a significantly smaller group, highlighting the dominance of regular users.

  3. Gender Distribution: The majority of riders were male, followed by female. Some users selected "Other" as their gender, though this group had a smaller sample size and exhibited higher variation in trip duration.

  4. Age Distribution: Most riders were born between 1980 and 2000, but there were some unrealistic values (e.g., birth years before 1900), likely due to data entry errors.

  5. Peak Usage Patterns: Weekday peaks occurred during morning and evening rush hours (8 AM & 5-6 PM), reflecting commuter behavior. Weekends had higher afternoon activity (12 PM - 4 PM), indicating leisure trips.

  6. Trip Duration by User Type: Customers took longer trips on average compared to subscribers, who had more consistent trip durations.

  7. Day of Week Usage Patterns: Subscribers had higher usage on weekdays, particularly on Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday. There was a noticeable drop in the number of trips on weekends, with Sunday having the lowest number of trips. Customers, on the other hand, showed more evenly distributed usage throughout the week, with a slight increase on weekends, especially on Saturday.
